{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6ce378e0-de5c-42db-a557-3357e6751984","content":"This is a TUnit project running on Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). TUnit uses `--treenode-filter` with a path pattern of `/<assembly>/<namespace>/<class>/<test>`.\n\nThe command is:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nThe wildcards (`*`) match any assembly and namespace, filtering down to just the `SmsNotificationTests` class — which includes `SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2665c001-1e7f-4bba-b54a-825d829cf8f2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project (v0.6.120) using Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. TUnit uses its own filter syntax called \"treenode-filter\" rather than VSTest's `--filter`.\n\nFor TUnit on MTP, to filter by class name, you use:\n\n```\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nThe treenode filter pattern is `/<assembly>/<namespace>/<class>/<test>`. Using `*` as wildcards for assembly and namespace.\n\nWait, let me think about this more carefully. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform. The filter syntax for MTP with TUnit uses `--treenode-filter`. The pattern format is:\n\n\n`/assembly/namespace/class/method`\n\nSo to filter by class: `/*/*/SmsNotificationTests`\n\nI'm fairly confident about TUnit's filter syntax. For TUnit with MTP, the command would be:\n\n```\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nThough I should verify whether this project has `EnableMSTestRunner` or similar configured, since TUnit 0.6.x uses MTP by default with `OutputType: Exe`.\n\nThe csproj confirms it's using MTP with `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>`, so the treenode-filter approach with the path pattern `/<assembly>/<namespace>/<class>/<test>` should work to filter all tests in the `SmsNotificationTests` class.","outputTokens":576,"requestId":"981A:180764:205FCA:2A5FF7:69FFDF31"},"id":"74